Using cotton buds to remove earwax is not necessary and is in fact dangerous - it can cause permanent deafness.

STEP 1: GET A PIECE OF PAPER

Make sure the paper has no crumple marks. Wrinkles will create shadows and will ruin the effect. Avoid glossy paper as well, as it will reflect back too much light and possibly create white streaks (highlights) on your subject.

STEP 2: GO TO A PLACE WITH BRIGHT LIGHT

Natural lighting or a bright indoor white lamp. The light will bleach the paper, removing any minor blemishes.

STEP 3: PREPARE A RAMP

Do you watch skateboarding in X-games? Prepare a slope that looks like that. Position the paper against a wall, tape it and let the loose side
rest on a flat surface.

STEP 4: POSITION YOUR SUBJECT

Put your subject in the middle. As much as possible, try to avoid "seeing" the edges of the paper when framing your shot. It will make it easier during post processing.

Use flash or not? Unless you have a mounted flash unit that you can swivel to a different direction, avoid using flash.

We see it all the time - but what the heck really is contrast?

In simplest words - it's the difference between the darkest areas in an image against the brightest ones. Increasing the contrast settings on a photo simply makes the already bright stuff even brighter and the dark ones duller. The more you combine the 2 extremes in a frame, the higher contrast.

Yellow falls into the bright end, mix it with black and you get an eye-catching image. The above photo courtesy of @krisco is a stunning example of high contrast at work: edit-free.

Before shooting, look for the brightest and darkest areas, then make high contrast work for you. Capturing it on the spot is always better than post-processing. Share it with us under the tag #photogeekdom_hicontrast.

[Photography Tip]

Before Photoshop effects and Instagram filters were invented - there were the real filters. A filter is a piece of glass that you attach in front on your camera lens to achieve a certain effect. Imagine letting your camera wear brown-tinted sunglasses -  you'd get sepia-colored shots right? 
Instead of a brown-tinted lens filter, Nick used a graduated filter. This type of filter allows you to take better landscape photos when the sun is too bright - it prevents the camera from overexposing the image (which makes the shot too white), resulting into shots with more colors. 
Quoting Nick @nickchillphoto: "Graduated filters are important tools for a landscape photographer. The top photo was taken using a Reverse Graduated Neutral Density Filter, no post-processing. [Photography Tip] What is motion blur? 
Motion blur is the intentional blurring when capturing moving objects, to produce a streaking effect. Doing this results into creative shots that suggest an illusion of movement.

To achieve motion blur, you will need a camera that allows you to control shutter speed manually. You need to rest your camera on a tripod or a stable surface and set the shutter to open 3 seconds or longer.

When moisture from the air, or from anywhere else, reaches an object with iron in it, oxygen in the water combines with atoms of iron to form molecules of a compound called iron oxide. The iron oxide particles remain suspended in the water, but when the water evaporates, the particles remain, forming a reddish coating on the surface of the iron. Without the presence of water, objects cannot rust. Other metals besides iron and steel can rust when exposed to moisture, but not all rust is ‚Äúrust-colored.‚Äù For instance, when copper or bronze rusts, it turns green. The green crust is called a patina. [source: bigsiteofamazingfacts.com] This is a bike handlebar, in case you're wondering what it is.

caption.text: Legend has it that it's a mortal sin to use a camera's built-in flash. It's not always true. There's only one statement to sum up the concept of the flash: it should always be unnoticeable. The most effective use of flash is when the photo appears like if you didn't use it. There are 2 ways to use the flash - to make it the main light or to make it a fill light. When using flash as the main light, it should appear as though the light is coming from an external source - which often is located at the top. That's why you see professional photographers aiming their flashes upwards - to make it bounce against the ceiling and thus create an indoor lighting effect. That what makes using the built in flash a sin - it's poised to direct the light at a horizontal angle - something which will only happen if you're in front of a car's headlights. It makes the photo unflattering, kills all texture and just makes you plain oily-looking. Try to lower the lighting of your flash or use a tissue to block it, so that it softens the blow. The second way to use flash - as a fill light will be discussed on later posts. Share your flash shots by tagging to #flashme_pg.

Unless something is glossy in nature, it will have some form of texture. The key technique in getting texture is lighting. It must come from a deep angle - either way from the side or from the top. By doing that, you are emphasizing the small bumps on the facade of the subject - which ultimately defines texture. Take a subject, turn off the lights and take a small light source, probably your iphone light and angle it from the side. See the results.
